This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) category as it deals with abnormal crowd behavior detection in video surveillance scenarios. It also involves the use of deep learning techniques such as Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) which are commonly used in computer vision tasks. 

The paper also involves the use of machine learning techniques for training and testing, which makes it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category. 

The use of GANs for generating normal distribution of data and the cross-channel approach for preventing G from learning a trivial identity function suggests that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) category. 

The paper involves the analysis of video data, which suggests that it may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) category. 

Finally, the paper deals with abnormal event detection in crowds, which may involve security and privacy concerns, making it likely to belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) category.
